title.narrative: IR 1.1: By 2018, maternal and neo-natal tetanos and polio are eradicated, under-five-y-o children mortality rate due to measles is reduced by 95%, and vaccination coverage for routine antigens is improved and maintained above 90% and the proportion of non or insufficiently- immunized children is reduced from 23% to 5%.

description.narrative: In 2019, the DRC was validated as having eliminated maternal and neonatal tetanus and also maintained its (wild) polio-free status, however, the main challenge faced was the increasing number of cVDPV2. A total of 2,768,250 children received Penta3 vaccine (88% of target) compared to 2,510,967 in 2018. During the reporting year, the country experienced a major measles outbreak and 2,666,322 children were vaccinated against measles (84% of target) compared to 2,470,873 in 2018. The DRC introduced a new vaccine (Rotavirus) and organized a national forum on vaccination. In addition, the Mashako plan was implemented in three provinces. | Status:Met | As-of Date:08/02/2020

actual.value: 2019:In July 2019, an assessment by experts from the WHO and UNICEF confirmed the elimination of maternal and neonatal tetanus in the DRC. This discovery confirms that the country currently has less than one case of neonatal tetanus per 1000 live births.
